\section{Available CubeMars Control Modes}
\label{sec:modes}
% =========================================================================

The AK60-6 V3.0 firmware exposes the following modes, all reachable through
\texttt{AK\_V3\_CAN.AkV3Motor} and the \texttt{ak\_v3\_bus.AkV3Bench} wrapper.

\begin{center}\small
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
Mode & Packet type & \texttt{data\_name} & Signal sent \\
\midrule
\textbf{MIT (force-control)} & \texttt{0x08} & \texttt{goal\_position} /
  \texttt{goal\_torque} & $K_p,K_d,q_d,\dot q_d,\tau_\mathrm{ff}$ \\
Position loop  & \texttt{0x04} & \texttt{goal\_position\_deg} & $q_d$ (degrees) \\
Velocity loop  & \texttt{0x03} & \texttt{goal\_speed\_erpm}   & $\omega_d$ (ERPM) \\
Current loop   & \texttt{0x01} & \texttt{goal\_duty}          & $I_q$ (duty) \\
Pos-vel profile& \texttt{0x06} & \texttt{goal\_pos\_spd}      & $q_d,\omega_d,\alpha$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\bigskip\noindent
The \textbf{MIT mode} is the most powerful because it lets the \emph{host}
choose the torque it commands:
\begin{equation}
  \tau = K_p(q_d - q) + K_d(\dot q_d - \dot q) + \tau_\mathrm{ff},
  \label{eq:mit}
\end{equation}
with $K_p\in[0,500]$ and $K_d\in[0,5]$ sent in the same CAN frame as the
setpoint.  Setting $K_p=K_d=0$ delivers a \emph{pure torque} $\tau_\mathrm{ff}$
directly from the current loop -- the fundamental building block for all
model-based controllers described below.

% =========================================================================
\section{Trajectory Generation}
\label{sec:traj}
% =========================================================================

A \emph{prescribed} end-effector trajectory $\vp_d(t)$, $\vpd_d(t)$,
$\vpdd_d(t)$ must be converted to joint-space references
$\vq_d(t)$, $\vqd_d(t)$, $\vqdd_d(t)$ before most joint-space controllers
can be applied.

\subsection{Inverse kinematics (closed-form, 2-DOF)}

\begin{equation}
  q_2 = \operatorname{atan2}\!\Bigl(\pm\sqrt{1-D^2},\, D\Bigr),
  \quad D = \frac{x^2+y^2-L_1^2-L_2^2}{2L_1 L_2},
  \label{eq:ik_q2}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
  q_1 = \operatorname{atan2}(y,x)
        - \operatorname{atan2}(L_2 s_2,\; L_1 + L_2 c_2).
  \label{eq:ik_q1}
\end{equation}
The $\pm$ sign selects elbow-up ($+$) or elbow-down ($-$) configuration.

\subsection{Joint velocity and acceleration from Jacobian}

Differentiate \eqref{eq:fk}:
\begin{equation}
  \vqd_d = \J^\dagger(\vq_d)\,\vpd_d, \qquad
  \vqdd_d = \J^\dagger(\vq_d)\bigl(\vpdd_d - \dot\J(\vq_d,\vqd_d)\,\vqd_d\bigr).
  \label{eq:jac_diff}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Minimum-jerk trajectory in Cartesian space}

For point-to-point moves from $\vp_0$ to $\vp_f$ in time $T$, the
minimum-jerk polynomial satisfies zero position, velocity, and acceleration
at both endpoints:
\begin{equation}
  \vp_d(t) = \vp_0 + (\vp_f - \vp_0)
    \Bigl[10\bigl(t/T\bigr)^3 - 15\bigl(t/T\bigr)^4
          + 6\bigl(t/T\bigr)^5\Bigr].
  \label{eq:minjerk}
\end{equation}

