\section{Two-Motor Implementation Architecture}
\label{sec:impl}
% =========================================================================

\subsection{Bus setup: two AkV3Bench instances}

Each motor lives on its own \texttt{AkV3Bench} (separate \texttt{can\_id}).
Both share the same SocketCAN bus handle:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Dual-motor setup}]
import can
from ak_v3_bus import AkV3Bench

# Open one SocketCAN bus shared by both motors
raw_bus = can.Bus(channel="can1", interface="socketcan")

shoulder = AkV3Bench(channel="can1", can_id=0x01,
                     model="AK60-6", name="shoulder")
elbow    = AkV3Bench(channel="can1", can_id=0x02,
                     model="AK60-6", name="elbow")

shoulder.connect(set_zero=True)
elbow.connect(   set_zero=True)
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Control loop skeleton}

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Generic 100-Hz control loop}]
import time
import numpy as np

DT = 0.01    # 100 Hz control loop
t0 = time.monotonic()

try:
    while True:
        t = time.monotonic() - t0

        # 1. Read joint state (one CAN round-trip each)
        q1, dq1, _ = shoulder.read_state()["shoulder"]
        q2, dq2, _ = elbow.read_state()["elbow"]
        q  = np.array([q1,  q2 ])
        dq = np.array([dq1, dq2])

        # 2. Evaluate reference trajectory at time t
        q_d, dqd, qdd_d = trajectory(t)   # user-defined function

        # 3. Compute control torques (select one controller below)
        tau = ctc_torque(q, dq, q_d, dqd, qdd_d)   # CTC
        # tau = cartpd_torque(q, dq, p_d(t), pd_d(t))  # Cartesian PD
        # tau = osc_torque(q, dq, p_d(t), pd_d(t), pdd_d(t))  # OSC

        # 4. Send commands (pure feedforward)
        shoulder.write("goal_torque", {"shoulder": tau[0]})
        elbow.write(   "goal_torque", {"elbow":    tau[1]})

        # 5. Pace loop
        time.sleep(max(0, DT - (time.monotonic() - t0 - t)))

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    pass
finally:
    shoulder.disconnect()
    elbow.disconnect()
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Feedback latency and timing}

Each \texttt{read\_state()} call triggers one MIT frame (to provoke a
reply in Query-Reply CAN mode) and blocks for up to 100\,ms.
For a two-joint arm this adds $\approx$2\,ms serialised latency per
control tick.  Mitigations:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Use \textbf{Periodic Feedback} mode (set via R-Link): motor
        auto-broadcasts at a fixed rate.  Parse frames in a
        background thread and read the latest cached state.
  \item Send both MIT commands \emph{before} reading feedback to
        reduce effective round-trip time.
  \item For CTC at $\omega_n\le 15$\,rad/s a 10\,ms loop with 2\,ms
        feedback latency introduces $<\!10\%$ phase margin loss -- still stable.
\end{itemize}

